Here's the approach:

### 1. Define three `ResourceDictionary` files

Create a XAML resource dictionary per theme (e.g., in a `Themes/` folder):

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
    <!-- …more keys… -->
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` using the **same keys** with different values.

### 2. Create a theme-switching service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d =>
            d is LightTheme or DarkTheme or HighContrastTheme);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        // Add the new one
        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new LightTheme()
        };
        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }
}
```

### 3. Load the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();

    var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
    if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

### 4. Bind controls with `DynamicResource`

Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
        Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(ThemePicker.SelectedItem?.ToString(), out var t))
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(t);
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- Every theme dictionary must share the **same keys**.
- Always use **`DynamicResource`** so swapping the dictionary triggers live updates.
- **`Preferences`** persists the choice across launches.
